WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:06.240 --> 00:00:09.370
SPEAKER: And then joining us
today is Helder Guimaraes.

00:00:09.370 --> 00:00:12.570
Helder is a world renowned
sleight of hand magician.

00:00:12.570 --> 00:00:15.710
He's received top honors
from the Academy of Magical

00:00:15.710 --> 00:00:19.370
Arts in Hollywood, and in
2006 became the youngest ever

00:00:19.370 --> 00:00:21.350
world champion of card magic.

00:00:21.350 --> 00:00:23.090
The "New York Times"
has described him

00:00:23.090 --> 00:00:25.390
as a master of illusions.

00:00:25.390 --> 00:00:28.718
And in the review of his
last show, "Borrowed Time,"

00:00:28.718 --> 00:00:30.260
the "Los Angeles
Times" described him

00:00:30.260 --> 00:00:32.140
as remarkably sincere
and trustworthy

00:00:32.140 --> 00:00:34.220
for a man committed
to deception.

00:00:34.220 --> 00:00:37.370
His newest one man show
is "Invisible Tango,"

00:00:37.370 --> 00:00:41.090
featuring direction by "Jurassic
World" producer Frank Marshall.

00:00:41.090 --> 00:00:44.390
And just announced an
original soundtrack by Moby.

00:00:44.390 --> 00:00:45.890
So Helder, thank
you for joining us.

00:00:45.890 --> 00:00:48.140
HELDER GUIMARAES: Thank you
very much for inviting me.

00:00:48.140 --> 00:00:48.662
[APPLAUSE]

00:00:48.662 --> 00:00:51.057
Thank you.

00:00:51.057 --> 00:00:52.640
SPEAKER: So first
off, I'd like to get

00:00:52.640 --> 00:00:54.800
into your background a bit.

00:00:54.800 --> 00:00:56.600
How did you get
into magic, and what

00:00:56.600 --> 00:00:59.900
drew you to sleight
of hand in particular?

00:00:59.900 --> 00:01:03.620
HELDER GUIMARAES:
So my father was

00:01:03.620 --> 00:01:07.580
kind of the reason why
I started in magic.

00:01:07.580 --> 00:01:11.630
My father did and still
does magic as a hobby.

00:01:11.630 --> 00:01:16.460
And when I was
three days old, he

00:01:16.460 --> 00:01:20.330
took a photo of me holding
playing cards, which

00:01:20.330 --> 00:01:24.890
is very ridiculous because it's
a three-day-old baby holding

00:01:24.890 --> 00:01:26.720
playing cards.

00:01:26.720 --> 00:01:29.660
And that was something that
was always a little bit

00:01:29.660 --> 00:01:34.160
on the back of my
imagination, growing up,

00:01:34.160 --> 00:01:37.190
knowing that that was the
first photo that anyone--

00:01:37.190 --> 00:01:41.790
yeah, I was born in '82.

00:01:41.790 --> 00:01:43.160
And in '82, there was no phones.

00:01:43.160 --> 00:01:46.720
So people would not take photos
as the birth is happening.

00:01:46.720 --> 00:01:48.580
It would take some
days to take photos.

00:01:48.580 --> 00:01:51.260
So with three days old,
they take my first photo,

00:01:51.260 --> 00:01:54.560
and that's with
the playing cards.

00:01:54.560 --> 00:01:57.230
And fast forward
a couple of years.

00:01:57.230 --> 00:02:02.240
When I was three, there
was a Christmas party

00:02:02.240 --> 00:02:04.070
in my kindergarten.

00:02:04.070 --> 00:02:06.140
And the owner of
the kindergarten

00:02:06.140 --> 00:02:09.410
knew that my father did magic.

00:02:09.410 --> 00:02:10.910
So he said, you
want to do something

00:02:10.910 --> 00:02:13.730
for Helder's class
and the classmates?

00:02:13.730 --> 00:02:15.590
And he said, sure, I'll do it.

00:02:15.590 --> 00:02:18.710
And my father asked me, do
you want to do something?

00:02:18.710 --> 00:02:20.453
And I'm three.

00:02:20.453 --> 00:02:21.870
What do I know
about [INAUDIBLE]??

00:02:21.870 --> 00:02:22.828
I was like, yeah, sure.

00:02:22.828 --> 00:02:25.150
So I'll do it.

00:02:25.150 --> 00:02:30.890
And it was fun because all
of the sudden, I'm three.

00:02:30.890 --> 00:02:35.480
Actually, when the show
happened, I was already four.

00:02:35.480 --> 00:02:38.800
So I was a big guy at that time.

00:02:38.800 --> 00:02:42.770
But basically,
there was a moment

00:02:42.770 --> 00:02:45.120
where I did something
very simple,

00:02:45.120 --> 00:02:51.200
but for the class, for
my kindergarten class,

00:02:51.200 --> 00:02:53.210
was like the best thing ever.

00:02:53.210 --> 00:02:54.460
I had a box.

00:02:54.460 --> 00:02:55.510
I would open the box.

00:02:55.510 --> 00:02:56.750
I would show the box empty.

00:02:56.750 --> 00:02:59.250
I would close the box.

00:02:59.250 --> 00:03:00.560
I would say the magic words.

00:03:00.560 --> 00:03:04.430
I would open the box, and the
box was filled with candies.

00:03:04.430 --> 00:03:09.567
And I start throwing the
candies out for the classmate.

00:03:09.567 --> 00:03:10.400
Not happening today.

00:03:10.400 --> 00:03:11.240
SPEAKER: That's not
happening today.

00:03:11.240 --> 00:03:12.823
HELDER GUIMARAES:
Not happening today.

00:03:14.960 --> 00:03:19.610
And all of the sudden, I'm the
hero for a couple of weeks.

00:03:19.610 --> 00:03:23.180
Like this is our friend
that makes candy appear.

00:03:23.180 --> 00:03:26.880
That's the guy to hang out with.

00:03:26.880 --> 00:03:30.190
And I think that was kind of
an interesting moment in terms

00:03:30.190 --> 00:03:33.590
of memory, because I still
remember the feeling of,

00:03:33.590 --> 00:03:37.015
in the weeks following that
party, kids coming to me

00:03:37.015 --> 00:03:38.390
and going like,
that was amazing.

00:03:38.390 --> 00:03:40.070
That was great.

00:03:40.070 --> 00:03:44.720
And I just kept doing it, a
little bit without knowing

00:03:44.720 --> 00:03:45.890
where it would take me.

00:03:45.890 --> 00:03:47.460
It just made sense.

00:03:47.460 --> 00:03:50.660
So I kept evolving, doing a
little bit more complex things,

00:03:50.660 --> 00:03:53.360
doing more interesting things.

00:03:53.360 --> 00:03:59.090
Around the age of
nine, I think nine, 10,

00:03:59.090 --> 00:04:02.210
that's when I went like, I
don't know if this is for me.

00:04:02.210 --> 00:04:03.470
And I stop.

00:04:03.470 --> 00:04:07.790
And I just stopped
for two, three months.

00:04:07.790 --> 00:04:09.950
And then I was
like, you know what?

00:04:09.950 --> 00:04:11.000
I can't.

00:04:11.000 --> 00:04:12.340
I really have to do this.

00:04:12.340 --> 00:04:14.450
I didn't know why, but
there was something

00:04:14.450 --> 00:04:18.240
that was pushing me to go back.

00:04:18.240 --> 00:04:21.200
So I went basically
back to doing magic

00:04:21.200 --> 00:04:22.980
without knowing
why I was doing it,

00:04:22.980 --> 00:04:26.280
but having the feeling
that I have to do it.

00:04:26.280 --> 00:04:29.987
And eventually, at that time--

00:04:29.987 --> 00:04:31.820
now I'm going to go a
little bit technical--

00:04:31.820 --> 00:04:34.740
but when you are a kid,
your hands are smaller.

00:04:34.740 --> 00:04:37.190
So you can't really
do sleight of hand

00:04:37.190 --> 00:04:39.470
the same way you can do
when you start growing up.

00:04:39.470 --> 00:04:42.680
But when you are 12, you
start going to that phase.

00:04:42.680 --> 00:04:47.090
11, 12, you start having the
ability to at least start

00:04:47.090 --> 00:04:48.470
on that route.

00:04:48.470 --> 00:04:52.670
And at that point,
I've seen a show.

00:04:52.670 --> 00:04:54.540
I went to Madrid.

00:04:54.540 --> 00:05:00.380
And I saw a show of a magician
that I've seen videos of him

00:05:00.380 --> 00:05:01.280
before.

00:05:01.280 --> 00:05:07.830
Not on the internet, but
on VHS, which good times.

00:05:07.830 --> 00:05:09.570
But I've seen a bunch
of videos from him.

00:05:09.570 --> 00:05:12.510
And now I got the
opportunity to see him live.

00:05:12.510 --> 00:05:14.550
And he was amazing.

00:05:14.550 --> 00:05:16.750
Because he was still alive.

00:05:16.750 --> 00:05:18.420
His name is Juan Tamariz.

00:05:18.420 --> 00:05:21.660
He had a bunch of
TV shows in Spain.

00:05:21.660 --> 00:05:26.760
But all his work revolves
around playing cards

00:05:26.760 --> 00:05:28.740
and the sense of humor.

00:05:28.740 --> 00:05:32.340
And that for me just all of
the sudden made complete sense.

00:05:32.340 --> 00:05:34.560
And I went like, this is it.

00:05:34.560 --> 00:05:37.080
I always loved humors.

00:05:37.080 --> 00:05:39.060
I always loved comedians.

00:05:39.060 --> 00:05:40.380
I loved magic.

00:05:40.380 --> 00:05:43.080
I said, I know this is it.

00:05:43.080 --> 00:05:47.580
I don't want to be him, but I
know that these two things are

00:05:47.580 --> 00:05:50.010
going to be part of my journey.

00:05:50.010 --> 00:05:51.900
And so then I start
to focus on playing

00:05:51.900 --> 00:05:53.860
cards and sleight of hand.

00:05:53.860 --> 00:05:56.958
And then it evolved from there.

00:05:56.958 --> 00:05:57.750
SPEAKER: Excellent.

00:05:57.750 --> 00:05:58.470
Thank you.

00:05:58.470 --> 00:05:59.640
And then so--

00:05:59.640 --> 00:06:02.290
HELDER GUIMARAES: I give
really long answers.

00:06:02.290 --> 00:06:06.600
So just for you to know, next
time you ask me something,

00:06:06.600 --> 00:06:07.837
just be careful.

00:06:07.837 --> 00:06:08.670
SPEAKER: Duly noted.

00:06:11.660 --> 00:06:18.170
So then [INAUDIBLE] going
from just magic as a hobby

00:06:18.170 --> 00:06:19.760
to professional magic.

00:06:19.760 --> 00:06:22.890
So in 2006, you won the
World Championship of Magic.

00:06:22.890 --> 00:06:25.280
And that's what kind
of launched your career

00:06:25.280 --> 00:06:26.290
into professional magic.

00:06:26.290 --> 00:06:28.730
Also, from what I've heard,
there was a bit of controversy

00:06:28.730 --> 00:06:29.230
there.

00:06:29.230 --> 00:06:31.533
They didn't believe your
performance was possible.

00:06:31.533 --> 00:06:32.450
HELDER GUIMARAES: Yes.

00:06:32.450 --> 00:06:33.932
SPEAKER: It's amazing.

00:06:33.932 --> 00:06:35.390
So yeah, can you
tell a little more

00:06:35.390 --> 00:06:43.340
how you then became a
professional at magic, I guess?

00:06:43.340 --> 00:06:49.130
HELDER GUIMARAES: Well, that's
actually a very short answer.

00:06:49.130 --> 00:06:51.130
Basically, you become
a professional at magic

00:06:51.130 --> 00:06:56.880
when you get paid to do
it on a regular basis.

00:06:56.880 --> 00:06:58.850
SPEAKER: OK. [? Fascinating. ?]

00:06:58.850 --> 00:07:01.760
HELDER GUIMARAES:
Now, you tell me--

00:07:01.760 --> 00:07:04.910
I think what you want to
know is how I kind of went

00:07:04.910 --> 00:07:06.210
into that direction.

00:07:06.210 --> 00:07:10.700
So I think since I'm 16, 17,
I kind of go like, I really

00:07:10.700 --> 00:07:12.470
want to be a magician.

00:07:12.470 --> 00:07:15.650
That's what I want to be.

00:07:15.650 --> 00:07:18.770
You never know if it's possible
or not, especially growing up

00:07:18.770 --> 00:07:20.150
in Portugal.

00:07:20.150 --> 00:07:23.000
It's not necessarily
the country that

00:07:23.000 --> 00:07:29.000
is best known for magic or to
be able to live comfortably

00:07:29.000 --> 00:07:31.250
from just doing magic.

00:07:31.250 --> 00:07:34.340
So in my head, I
always knew that if I

00:07:34.340 --> 00:07:36.170
wanted to become a
magician, I would

00:07:36.170 --> 00:07:40.010
have to search for a more
international career.

00:07:40.010 --> 00:07:45.030
And one of the ways of
starting that career,

00:07:45.030 --> 00:07:49.460
I knew it would be to
win a prize at the World

00:07:49.460 --> 00:07:52.370
Championship of Magic,
because that would just

00:07:52.370 --> 00:07:58.700
trigger a lot of invitations
and people trying to hire you.

00:07:58.700 --> 00:08:00.230
So I knew that.

00:08:00.230 --> 00:08:06.500
So a few years before, actually
four years before that,

00:08:06.500 --> 00:08:08.720
I went to theater school.

00:08:08.720 --> 00:08:11.915
Because I knew that
was another thing,

00:08:11.915 --> 00:08:15.920
is that in the
journey to find, let's

00:08:15.920 --> 00:08:18.350
say, my path, all
of the sudden I

00:08:18.350 --> 00:08:22.760
randomly encounter myself
doing theater and doing

00:08:22.760 --> 00:08:24.110
theater workshops.

00:08:24.110 --> 00:08:26.910
And it makes sense to me to
combine all those things--

00:08:26.910 --> 00:08:28.970
humor, theater, and magic.

00:08:28.970 --> 00:08:33.200
And so I have to
go to university.

00:08:33.200 --> 00:08:35.990
Actually, the first
university I went to

00:08:35.990 --> 00:08:39.320
was for computer science.

00:08:39.320 --> 00:08:43.880
So I could have actually
been here, but seated there.

00:08:43.880 --> 00:08:49.070
But I really don't know how you
guys spend so much time sitting

00:08:49.070 --> 00:08:52.010
in front of computers.

00:08:52.010 --> 00:08:58.490
The first year I went to
university in computer science,

00:08:58.490 --> 00:09:01.580
we had group tasks
that we had to do

00:09:01.580 --> 00:09:04.340
and with a group of four people.

00:09:04.340 --> 00:09:06.320
And three of them
would be sitting

00:09:06.320 --> 00:09:10.970
in front of the screen working,
and I would be making jokes

00:09:10.970 --> 00:09:11.990
to entertain them.

00:09:11.990 --> 00:09:16.038
That's basically my
first year in college.

00:09:16.038 --> 00:09:17.330
And then I went, you know what?

00:09:17.330 --> 00:09:19.640
Maybe I shouldn't be doing this.

00:09:19.640 --> 00:09:23.250
And I really had a talk with
my father and my mother.

00:09:23.250 --> 00:09:26.870
And I said, I know
I can do this.

00:09:26.870 --> 00:09:30.590
But I am not going to
be happy, and I'm not

00:09:30.590 --> 00:09:32.540
going to be able to
do this professionally

00:09:32.540 --> 00:09:33.750
for the rest of my life.

00:09:33.750 --> 00:09:36.800
So I really want to
go and study theater,

00:09:36.800 --> 00:09:38.840
because I think it
can help with magic.

00:09:38.840 --> 00:09:43.260
Which for my father loves magic,
my mother loves magic as well.

00:09:43.260 --> 00:09:46.550
But as a father and mother,
they were very worried

00:09:46.550 --> 00:09:47.420
about my future.

00:09:47.420 --> 00:09:52.340
So they really were like, if
he wants to be a magician,

00:09:52.340 --> 00:09:58.790
and his backup plan
is theater, you're not

00:09:58.790 --> 00:10:01.550
making right choices.

00:10:01.550 --> 00:10:03.800
But they finally
heard me, and they

00:10:03.800 --> 00:10:09.110
understand I was going
to pursue it anyway.

00:10:09.110 --> 00:10:10.160
So we made a pact.

00:10:10.160 --> 00:10:14.330
And the pact was, you
go to theater school.

00:10:14.330 --> 00:10:16.910
You have four
years to finish it.

00:10:16.910 --> 00:10:18.150
That's the degree length.

00:10:18.150 --> 00:10:21.800
So you have four
years to finish it.

00:10:21.800 --> 00:10:24.290
After the fourth year,
you have one year

00:10:24.290 --> 00:10:26.780
to become fully independent.

00:10:26.780 --> 00:10:30.830
If you can't do that, you
go back to computer science,

00:10:30.830 --> 00:10:32.480
and you finish the degree.

00:10:32.480 --> 00:10:34.920
And I go like, deal.

00:10:34.920 --> 00:10:37.468
So I went to theater school.

00:10:37.468 --> 00:10:38.510
Those are the four years.

00:10:38.510 --> 00:10:40.020
I've learned a lot.

00:10:40.020 --> 00:10:43.190
I've met other people that
were very like minded,

00:10:43.190 --> 00:10:45.860
not magician wise,
but they were trying

00:10:45.860 --> 00:10:50.480
to combine different things
with theater and performance art

00:10:50.480 --> 00:10:52.460
and dance, for example.

00:10:52.460 --> 00:10:54.170
And so all of the
sudden, I find myself

00:10:54.170 --> 00:10:56.420
that I'm in a group
of people that I can

00:10:56.420 --> 00:10:58.730
grow up with and learn from.

00:10:58.730 --> 00:11:02.780
During those four years,
I start doing small shows

00:11:02.780 --> 00:11:05.330
around my own town.

00:11:05.330 --> 00:11:06.890
I got a lot of stage time.

00:11:06.890 --> 00:11:08.555
That was a very helpful thing.

00:11:11.960 --> 00:11:14.402
I know this is a long
answer, but I warned you.

00:11:14.402 --> 00:11:15.110
SPEAKER: You did.

00:11:15.110 --> 00:11:16.850
HELDER GUIMARAES:
There was a place that

00:11:16.850 --> 00:11:19.490
was doing a lot of theater
shows and comedy shows,

00:11:19.490 --> 00:11:20.775
but they had no magic show.

00:11:20.775 --> 00:11:23.150
And a friend of mine was
working one of the comedy shows,

00:11:23.150 --> 00:11:25.430
and he said, you should
talk with this guy

00:11:25.430 --> 00:11:29.010
to see if he wants to
have you work there.

00:11:29.010 --> 00:11:29.510
OK.

00:11:29.510 --> 00:11:30.932
I went there.

00:11:30.932 --> 00:11:31.890
I said, I'm a magician.

00:11:31.890 --> 00:11:34.400
I would love to be able
to bring a show here.

00:11:34.400 --> 00:11:36.260
And he was like, eh,
we've had a magician.

00:11:36.260 --> 00:11:39.240
We really don't want magic.

00:11:39.240 --> 00:11:42.410
And I was like, OK,
how many music shows

00:11:42.410 --> 00:11:44.240
do you have here per month?

00:11:44.240 --> 00:11:45.350
Six, seven?

00:11:45.350 --> 00:11:50.120
And then I go, like, if you
had one bad music concert,

00:11:50.120 --> 00:11:52.127
would you stop doing music?

00:11:52.127 --> 00:11:53.210
And he kind of understood.

00:11:53.210 --> 00:11:55.880
So he brought me,
and I did a show.

00:11:55.880 --> 00:11:58.010
It was a room for 120 people.

00:11:58.010 --> 00:12:01.500
I think I had like
40 or 45 people.

00:12:01.500 --> 00:12:02.840
But I did a good show.

00:12:02.840 --> 00:12:03.800
He liked it.

00:12:03.800 --> 00:12:04.550
People liked it.

00:12:04.550 --> 00:12:06.570
He said come back with
the same show next month.

00:12:06.570 --> 00:12:08.270
So I brought the same show.

00:12:08.270 --> 00:12:10.247
Next month we had
like 60 people.

00:12:10.247 --> 00:12:12.080
And he said, well, if
you want to come back,

00:12:12.080 --> 00:12:14.100
you have to bring
a different show.

00:12:14.100 --> 00:12:16.620
But I'll give you two
dates on the same month.

00:12:16.620 --> 00:12:20.180
So the next month, I
create a full one hour

00:12:20.180 --> 00:12:24.770
show for the venue, different
than the one before.

00:12:24.770 --> 00:12:26.210
We did two dates.

00:12:26.210 --> 00:12:29.450
And he said, OK, bring the same
show back to the next month.

00:12:29.450 --> 00:12:32.480
OK, so now I'm doing the
same show four times.

00:12:32.480 --> 00:12:36.500
The fifth month, he tells me,
I can give you four dates,

00:12:36.500 --> 00:12:41.010
but you have to change
the show every month now.

00:12:41.010 --> 00:12:42.550
And I was like, you know what?

00:12:42.550 --> 00:12:43.680
Let's do it.

00:12:43.680 --> 00:12:49.040
So for two years, every month I
was doing a different one hour

00:12:49.040 --> 00:12:50.570
performance.

00:12:50.570 --> 00:12:53.960
And so that just give me
a lot of stage time doing

00:12:53.960 --> 00:12:56.270
what I like, creating things.

00:12:56.270 --> 00:13:02.000
So it just made me really
think about magic in a way

00:13:02.000 --> 00:13:04.160
that I still think
today, but it helped

00:13:04.160 --> 00:13:06.740
me just develop a lot of--

00:13:06.740 --> 00:13:09.560
you have no time
to make judgments

00:13:09.560 --> 00:13:12.500
if things are in the right way.

00:13:12.500 --> 00:13:14.660
So sometimes you get on
stage, and you get really

00:13:14.660 --> 00:13:15.903
awkward moments.

00:13:15.903 --> 00:13:16.820
But that was the time.

00:13:16.820 --> 00:13:17.880
That was the time to do it.

00:13:17.880 --> 00:13:19.338
That was the right
moment to do it.

00:13:19.338 --> 00:13:24.390
So those are the two years prior
to the World Champion of Magic.

00:13:24.390 --> 00:13:29.270
So I really was very comfortable
when it came to go there

00:13:29.270 --> 00:13:31.280
and just do 10 minutes.

00:13:31.280 --> 00:13:33.900
Because basically, that's
what you have to do.

00:13:33.900 --> 00:13:35.660
So I've been doing
one hour shows

00:13:35.660 --> 00:13:38.120
different for two years almost.

00:13:38.120 --> 00:13:41.750
So 10 minutes seemed like,
I think I can do this.

00:13:41.750 --> 00:13:44.660
But I wasn't super confident
that I'm going to go there,

00:13:44.660 --> 00:13:46.055
and I'm going to win.

00:13:46.055 --> 00:13:47.180
I wasn't confident on that.

00:13:47.180 --> 00:13:51.800
I just knew that I could
select 10 really good minutes

00:13:51.800 --> 00:13:55.875
to go there and have an impact.

00:13:55.875 --> 00:13:56.750
So that's what I did.

00:13:56.750 --> 00:14:01.610
I start working on the
routine a year before.

00:14:01.610 --> 00:14:04.040
I had the concept of
what I wanted to do.

00:14:04.040 --> 00:14:06.430
I started developing it.

00:14:06.430 --> 00:14:11.240
I went to a couple of
competitions, one in Spain,

00:14:11.240 --> 00:14:13.850
where I actually won
the prize as well,

00:14:13.850 --> 00:14:18.990
and another one in England,
where I didn't even place.

00:14:18.990 --> 00:14:20.300
Which is fine.

00:14:20.300 --> 00:14:22.280
That's how things are.

00:14:22.280 --> 00:14:24.560
And then I go to the
World Championship in 2006

00:14:24.560 --> 00:14:27.380
in Sweden, Stockholm.

00:14:27.380 --> 00:14:29.940
I go inside of the room--

00:14:29.940 --> 00:14:35.110
well actually, five
minutes before there

00:14:35.110 --> 00:14:38.560
was this moment
where technically I

00:14:38.560 --> 00:14:43.510
should be extremely nervous,
but I was extremely calm.

00:14:43.510 --> 00:14:45.730
And I don't even
know why, because I

00:14:45.730 --> 00:14:48.893
didn't have that much
experience at the time.

00:14:48.893 --> 00:14:51.310
But I just had this moment
where it's like, you know what?

00:14:51.310 --> 00:14:52.330
Just have fun.

00:14:52.330 --> 00:14:54.370
Just go out there, have fun.

00:14:54.370 --> 00:14:56.230
So I entered the room.

00:14:56.230 --> 00:14:59.080
I would say that from--

00:14:59.080 --> 00:15:04.780
so it's 3,000
magicians watching you.

00:15:04.780 --> 00:15:08.320
Although the room for what I
do-- because I do it close up,

00:15:08.320 --> 00:15:12.670
the room I think maybe would
sit 200 people I would say.

00:15:12.670 --> 00:15:14.410
But there were
monitors broadcasting

00:15:14.410 --> 00:15:16.580
to other rooms and outside.

00:15:16.580 --> 00:15:21.870
So from those 200 people,
maybe 20 people knew who I was.

00:15:21.870 --> 00:15:23.800
So I got in the room.

00:15:23.800 --> 00:15:25.840
I get a nice round of applause.

00:15:25.840 --> 00:15:27.040
People welcomed me.

00:15:27.040 --> 00:15:28.630
I go.

00:15:28.630 --> 00:15:31.120
I don't remember
anything I've done.

00:15:31.120 --> 00:15:36.400
So in my head, it was just
like, fuck it [INAUDIBLE]..

00:15:36.400 --> 00:15:37.600
I don't know.

00:15:37.600 --> 00:15:41.260
And all I know is at the end,
I'm having a standing ovation.

00:15:41.260 --> 00:15:43.490
And I'm coming out of that room.

00:15:43.490 --> 00:15:47.050
And as I walk outside, I
have people coming to me

00:15:47.050 --> 00:15:51.760
and go like, what the
fuck just happened?

00:15:51.760 --> 00:15:54.670
And it was just this
very surreal moment

00:15:54.670 --> 00:16:01.390
because what I was at
that moment didn't change.

00:16:01.390 --> 00:16:03.370
That was who I was.

00:16:03.370 --> 00:16:07.180
But all of the sudden, there
were 3,000 magicians that knew

00:16:07.180 --> 00:16:10.060
my name, that 10
minutes before didn't.

00:16:10.060 --> 00:16:13.120
And that was kind
of an eye opener,

00:16:13.120 --> 00:16:15.830
that sometimes it's
not who you are,

00:16:15.830 --> 00:16:19.420
but it's how people see you
that really changes and makes

00:16:19.420 --> 00:16:21.010
an impact.

00:16:21.010 --> 00:16:25.630
Two days after that, they
announced the winners.

00:16:25.630 --> 00:16:30.490
And actually I knew I won before
they announced, because there

00:16:30.490 --> 00:16:34.870
is this moment at the end of the
convention where the winners go

00:16:34.870 --> 00:16:37.720
on stage, and they
perform for everyone.

00:16:37.720 --> 00:16:40.570
And normally they
have everyone that

00:16:40.570 --> 00:16:45.520
got more than 80 points
on score to perform.

00:16:45.520 --> 00:16:48.123
So even if you
have more than 80,

00:16:48.123 --> 00:16:49.540
it doesn't mean
you are the first.

00:16:49.540 --> 00:16:52.210
Because if in your category
two people have more than that,

00:16:52.210 --> 00:16:54.160
one is first, and the
other one is second.

00:16:54.160 --> 00:16:56.822
But in my category,
I was the only one

00:16:56.822 --> 00:16:58.030
that got more than 80 points.

00:16:58.030 --> 00:16:59.405
So when they
announced the names,

00:16:59.405 --> 00:17:03.430
it was very clear
that oh, I've won.

00:17:03.430 --> 00:17:06.160
I wasn't even in the
room when they did that.

00:17:06.160 --> 00:17:09.040
So my parents were there.

00:17:09.040 --> 00:17:11.660
So they heard it.

00:17:11.660 --> 00:17:15.520
And they came out running
looking for me on the halls

00:17:15.520 --> 00:17:17.260
of the Convention Center.

00:17:17.260 --> 00:17:20.560
And I'm just walking with
a deck of cards in my hand,

00:17:20.560 --> 00:17:22.810
just walking.

00:17:22.810 --> 00:17:26.619
And all of a sudden
I see my mother--

00:17:26.619 --> 00:17:27.670
my father wasn't there--

00:17:27.670 --> 00:17:31.840
my mother running with a bunch
of other Portuguese people

00:17:31.840 --> 00:17:34.410
around her going like, you won!

00:17:34.410 --> 00:17:35.410
You won!

00:17:35.410 --> 00:17:37.780
And I'm like, what happened?

00:17:37.780 --> 00:17:38.750
I'm not aware.

00:17:38.750 --> 00:17:40.948
I think tomorrow is
the award ceremony.

00:17:40.948 --> 00:17:42.990
So I'm like, in my head
it's like, what happened?

00:17:42.990 --> 00:17:44.698
No, you're going to
go to the final gala.

00:17:44.698 --> 00:17:46.090
So you won.

00:17:46.090 --> 00:17:47.570
You are the only one--

00:17:47.570 --> 00:17:49.720
and so someone
kind of blocks me,

00:17:49.720 --> 00:17:51.490
and explains to
me what happened.

00:17:51.490 --> 00:17:53.260
And I was like, oh.

00:17:53.260 --> 00:17:55.720
And all of a
sudden, that dream--

00:17:55.720 --> 00:17:57.760
because to be honest
with you, I never

00:17:57.760 --> 00:18:01.120
wanted to have the title,
World Champion of Magic.

00:18:01.120 --> 00:18:02.440
That didn't matter to me.

00:18:02.440 --> 00:18:05.050
But there were other
people in that list

00:18:05.050 --> 00:18:08.140
of winners that were
mentors of mine,

00:18:08.140 --> 00:18:10.660
and people I really admired.

00:18:10.660 --> 00:18:13.510
And so for me, it
was more I made

00:18:13.510 --> 00:18:15.580
the list with people I admire.

00:18:15.580 --> 00:18:22.240
And so when I realized that, I
was so happy and really nervous

00:18:22.240 --> 00:18:26.420
because now you have to perform
as the World Champion of Magic.

00:18:26.420 --> 00:18:28.840
So it's a very
different stake now.

00:18:28.840 --> 00:18:31.570
But everything went fine.

00:18:31.570 --> 00:18:37.720
And so after that, I start
having calls and emails

00:18:37.720 --> 00:18:41.620
about going to Japan,
Australia, United States.

00:18:41.620 --> 00:18:43.540
My first travel to
the United States

00:18:43.540 --> 00:18:46.240
was because I won that prize.

00:18:46.240 --> 00:18:50.080
And I got booked
to do shows here.

00:18:50.080 --> 00:18:53.090
So another very long answer.

00:18:53.090 --> 00:18:54.600
SPEAKER: No, that's good.

00:18:54.600 --> 00:18:55.617
That's why we're here.

00:18:55.617 --> 00:18:56.950
They don't want to hear me talk.

00:18:59.750 --> 00:19:02.290
So getting back to your shows--

00:19:02.290 --> 00:19:04.780
and sounds like you're very
practiced creating shows--

00:19:04.780 --> 00:19:06.340
much of what you
do, sleight of hand,

00:19:06.340 --> 00:19:10.090
it's very up close, very
personal, as opposed to you're

00:19:10.090 --> 00:19:14.410
on a stage making
cars disappear.

00:19:14.410 --> 00:19:17.260
So how does that impact
the design of your shows,

00:19:17.260 --> 00:19:20.590
or what kind of performances
you choose to create?

00:19:20.590 --> 00:19:25.906
HELDER GUIMARAES: It's just the
type of thing I'm attracted to.

00:19:25.906 --> 00:19:30.730
I've always loved--
since I saw that show

00:19:30.730 --> 00:19:35.500
I mentioned in Madrid, I
really like the interaction

00:19:35.500 --> 00:19:36.790
with the audience.

00:19:36.790 --> 00:19:42.200
I really like the
fact that I never

00:19:42.200 --> 00:19:46.230
know what the audience is
going to do when I ask them.

00:19:46.230 --> 00:19:48.420
Even if it's a simple
thing or common gesture,

00:19:48.420 --> 00:19:50.450
just as pick a card.

00:19:50.450 --> 00:19:54.680
If I've told you all the
answers I've got from just that.

00:19:54.680 --> 00:19:57.680
You have the plain one,
which is just people actually

00:19:57.680 --> 00:20:00.140
go like, OK, let's collaborate.

00:20:00.140 --> 00:20:02.810
Other people go like, no,
no, no, no, no, no, no.

00:20:02.810 --> 00:20:06.770
I-- and then they start
like just messing around.

00:20:06.770 --> 00:20:07.670
You never know.

00:20:07.670 --> 00:20:10.970
And that for me is
really exciting.

00:20:10.970 --> 00:20:12.210
Because that's kind of life.

00:20:12.210 --> 00:20:12.710
You know?

00:20:12.710 --> 00:20:14.060
You never know.

00:20:14.060 --> 00:20:18.740
So I love that my shows have
that interaction component.

00:20:18.740 --> 00:20:23.210
Then there is the part of me
loving playing cards per se.

00:20:23.210 --> 00:20:25.040
I love the object.

00:20:25.040 --> 00:20:33.110
It's the symbolic side of
it, the fact that it evolved

00:20:33.110 --> 00:20:37.490
and through ages, but got
to a point where now a deck

00:20:37.490 --> 00:20:39.158
of cards, it's what it is.

00:20:39.158 --> 00:20:40.700
And it's never going
to change again.

00:20:40.700 --> 00:20:43.940
It's almost like a
perfect object in itself.

00:20:46.460 --> 00:20:50.600
And the variety
of things you can

00:20:50.600 --> 00:20:53.390
accomplish with
that unique object,

00:20:53.390 --> 00:20:56.360
that's the other part
that attracts me.

00:20:56.360 --> 00:21:00.350
And so all those
things combined end up

00:21:00.350 --> 00:21:03.860
making me want to
design my experiences

00:21:03.860 --> 00:21:05.810
around those things.

00:21:05.810 --> 00:21:10.070
A deck of cards, which means
that either you have a camera

00:21:10.070 --> 00:21:15.290
and projection, and then you can
have a bigger audience watching

00:21:15.290 --> 00:21:16.850
you.

00:21:16.850 --> 00:21:19.910
And I prefer not to, because
I think the camera always

00:21:19.910 --> 00:21:23.130
distance a little bit people
from the actual experience.

00:21:23.130 --> 00:21:25.220
So that means that
you have to design

00:21:25.220 --> 00:21:27.960
the experience for people
to be able to be near you

00:21:27.960 --> 00:21:29.540
and be able to see it.

00:21:32.520 --> 00:21:34.250
And then the interaction part.

00:21:34.250 --> 00:21:38.600
I don't want to be on a stage
where I can't actually have

00:21:38.600 --> 00:21:41.540
someone touch what I'm doing.

00:21:41.540 --> 00:21:45.750
So all those things
combined make that--

00:21:45.750 --> 00:21:50.010
I could have a car
on stage, but that

00:21:50.010 --> 00:21:54.600
would be the full stage
would be the size of the car.

00:21:54.600 --> 00:21:58.620
So it would not
be very practical.

00:21:58.620 --> 00:22:02.370
So I just want that
proximity to be part of it.

00:22:02.370 --> 00:22:06.120
And of course, that makes that--

00:22:06.120 --> 00:22:11.730
the next step about
it is, you end up

00:22:11.730 --> 00:22:13.830
deciding on things
that are very personal.

00:22:13.830 --> 00:22:17.550
And you end up telling stories
that are part of your life,

00:22:17.550 --> 00:22:20.100
and stories that can
make the audience

00:22:20.100 --> 00:22:22.830
relate to who you
are as a performer.

00:22:22.830 --> 00:22:29.490
And all those things combine
with my background in theater

00:22:29.490 --> 00:22:32.940
and me liking the
sense of humor,

00:22:32.940 --> 00:22:36.030
end up me mixing
all those things

00:22:36.030 --> 00:22:42.480
and just doing all the
things I like together.

00:22:42.480 --> 00:22:44.040
I'm very excited
about every time

00:22:44.040 --> 00:22:48.660
I'm creating a new
show, because I get--

00:22:48.660 --> 00:22:54.415
I think it's where
I feel more myself.

00:22:54.415 --> 00:22:59.160
I can't say I'm a shy
person, but I'm not

00:22:59.160 --> 00:23:03.570
as overt or as expansive
as I am on stage,

00:23:03.570 --> 00:23:04.980
when I'm out off stage.

00:23:04.980 --> 00:23:08.220
I have a bunch of funny
stories of people meeting me

00:23:08.220 --> 00:23:13.860
after shows and not realizing
it's me, because they go, how

00:23:13.860 --> 00:23:16.740
can you be the same
person that goes on stage

00:23:16.740 --> 00:23:20.790
and says all those things
and is so open about it,

00:23:20.790 --> 00:23:23.180
and then in here,
in the table, you

00:23:23.180 --> 00:23:27.300
are the only person
that was not speaking?

00:23:27.300 --> 00:23:30.600
And that is something
that changes me a bit,

00:23:30.600 --> 00:23:35.190
is when I go on stage, I
just become more comfortable.

00:23:35.190 --> 00:23:37.680
And I can't really explain why.

00:23:37.680 --> 00:23:38.590
SPEAKER: Makes sense.

00:23:38.590 --> 00:23:41.820
And so you described
yourself as a storyteller.

00:23:41.820 --> 00:23:44.960
And many of your shows,
you like to explore themes.

00:23:44.960 --> 00:23:47.370
"Invisible Tango"
is about mystery.

00:23:47.370 --> 00:23:51.010
Your last one, "Borrowed
Time," was about memory.

00:23:51.010 --> 00:23:54.510
So how does magic help
you tell the stories

00:23:54.510 --> 00:23:55.560
that you want to tell?

00:23:58.048 --> 00:23:59.590
HELDER GUIMARAES:
I don't think magic

00:23:59.590 --> 00:24:02.290
helps necessarily
tell the story,

00:24:02.290 --> 00:24:10.280
but gives it a perspective on
those themes and on who I am.

00:24:10.280 --> 00:24:16.570
And this is something
that it's easy to relate,

00:24:16.570 --> 00:24:19.860
but it's not necessarily
easy to explain.

00:24:19.860 --> 00:24:25.510
I look at things around
me as illusions or magic.

00:24:25.510 --> 00:24:27.990
So I'm always trying
to understand, where

00:24:27.990 --> 00:24:30.060
is something I'm not seeing?

00:24:30.060 --> 00:24:35.040
Or how I am seeing this, but
actually if I go to that angle,

00:24:35.040 --> 00:24:36.660
it looks different.

00:24:36.660 --> 00:24:40.570
I do that every 10
minutes in my life.

00:24:40.570 --> 00:24:47.400
So that's something I'm just
interested in, how people craft

00:24:47.400 --> 00:24:50.760
realities so that
you think it's real,

00:24:50.760 --> 00:24:54.450
but it's actually
what someone else did

00:24:54.450 --> 00:24:57.270
for you to believe it's real.

00:24:57.270 --> 00:25:03.210
Not going further, but just
look at politics and how that

00:25:03.210 --> 00:25:06.180
works on that specific area.

00:25:06.180 --> 00:25:10.620
So that happens in every
single thing in our life.

00:25:10.620 --> 00:25:12.780
And we just don't think
too much about that.

00:25:12.780 --> 00:25:14.680
I like to think about that.

00:25:14.680 --> 00:25:17.940
So when I approach those
subjects, like memory

00:25:17.940 --> 00:25:21.540
for example, or
mystery, I try to see it

00:25:21.540 --> 00:25:25.170
from the angle of a
magician looking at it.

00:25:25.170 --> 00:25:28.500
And so magic just is
a language that allows

00:25:28.500 --> 00:25:30.270
me to communicate those ideas.

00:25:32.880 --> 00:25:40.910
And because I incorporate other
things, like humor and theater,

00:25:40.910 --> 00:25:45.870
I can explore different
sides of the same theme,

00:25:45.870 --> 00:25:48.990
according to those
different languages,

00:25:48.990 --> 00:25:52.120
and create kind of
a unique moment.

00:25:52.120 --> 00:25:55.380
But for me, magic is not
different than theater

00:25:55.380 --> 00:25:55.950
or comedy.

00:25:55.950 --> 00:25:58.620
It's just an artistic
language that allows

00:25:58.620 --> 00:26:01.650
you to express a point of view.

00:26:01.650 --> 00:26:05.460
And eventually, my shows
have a point of view

00:26:05.460 --> 00:26:07.380
that is mine, because
I'm the one creating

00:26:07.380 --> 00:26:09.550
them and performing them.

00:26:09.550 --> 00:26:13.560
But I also always want the shows
to be open to interpretation

00:26:13.560 --> 00:26:17.040
so that whenever you bring
your own vision to what

00:26:17.040 --> 00:26:21.570
you're seeing, you
can make a decision.

00:26:21.570 --> 00:26:24.780
Or at least--

00:26:24.780 --> 00:26:29.280
I heard one time someone,
a plastic artist,

00:26:29.280 --> 00:26:33.600
that was saying, I
want people to come out

00:26:33.600 --> 00:26:38.280
of seeing my work with more
doubts than when they got in.

00:26:38.280 --> 00:26:41.190
And I don't
necessarily want people

00:26:41.190 --> 00:26:43.530
to be doubting all
their life when

00:26:43.530 --> 00:26:45.360
they go to see a show of mine.

00:26:45.360 --> 00:26:47.880
I think that's kind of
not very productive.

00:26:47.880 --> 00:26:51.240
But if you can question one
little thing in your life,

00:26:51.240 --> 00:26:53.940
that the next day you have to
make a decision [INAUDIBLE]

00:26:53.940 --> 00:26:55.305
you know what?

00:26:55.305 --> 00:26:57.180
Maybe there is something
here for me to think

00:26:57.180 --> 00:26:58.830
that I've never thought about.

00:26:58.830 --> 00:27:00.040
I'm happy with that.

00:27:00.040 --> 00:27:02.610
If you go out of my
show, and you go,

00:27:02.610 --> 00:27:05.130
I really had a great
time, that is something

00:27:05.130 --> 00:27:08.250
I'm very pleased about too.

00:27:08.250 --> 00:27:10.530
I think entertainment
for itself,

00:27:10.530 --> 00:27:15.240
it's something very valuable.

00:27:15.240 --> 00:27:19.290
But I always want people to
take something out of the show

00:27:19.290 --> 00:27:20.820
when they go.

00:27:20.820 --> 00:27:23.280
And I don't want them to
go, this is the truth.

00:27:23.280 --> 00:27:26.530
Because I don't believe
there is one truth.

