00:41:12.640 --> 00:41:16.060
So when I have a problem--

00:41:16.060 --> 00:41:19.920
and I really like to start
with problems that I go,

00:41:19.920 --> 00:41:23.200
I have no idea
how I can do this.

00:41:23.200 --> 00:41:27.420
So now, it's almost like,
this is the illusion.

00:41:27.420 --> 00:41:29.760
Because I know that
what I'm trying to do,

00:41:29.760 --> 00:41:31.500
it's actually impossible.

00:41:31.500 --> 00:41:34.920
So now it's, how can I
create this illusion?

00:41:34.920 --> 00:41:38.550
And now I kind of start
going back, step by step.

00:41:38.550 --> 00:41:42.180
If I want to reach this
moment, what would I

00:41:42.180 --> 00:41:45.060
have to do right before this?

00:41:45.060 --> 00:41:47.250
Maybe this, maybe
this, maybe this.

00:41:47.250 --> 00:41:50.910
And then you end up
with, I would say, maybe

00:41:50.910 --> 00:41:55.410
sometimes seven, eight,
sometimes more, sometimes less,

00:41:55.410 --> 00:41:57.480
basically solutions.

00:41:57.480 --> 00:41:59.620
And then you actually
start trying them.

00:41:59.620 --> 00:42:01.685
And you go like,
OK, let me try this.

00:42:01.685 --> 00:42:03.600
No, there is something
missing here.

00:42:03.600 --> 00:42:06.657
Or actually it's
not that deceptive.

00:42:06.657 --> 00:42:08.490
Because then you have
to make that judgment.

00:42:08.490 --> 00:42:10.590
It's like, is the
audience going to be

00:42:10.590 --> 00:42:13.750
deceived with this idea or not?

00:42:13.750 --> 00:42:17.460
So it's all those
things combine.

00:42:17.460 --> 00:42:20.130
And on the side, you always
have the story going like,

00:42:20.130 --> 00:42:22.710
that really does
not match the story.

00:42:22.710 --> 00:42:25.860
So this method is
completely discarded,

00:42:25.860 --> 00:42:30.570
because it's not faithful to
the story I want to convey.

00:42:30.570 --> 00:42:31.480
This one is closer.

00:42:31.480 --> 00:42:31.980
OK.

00:42:31.980 --> 00:42:34.530
So now this one is
something I can work on,

00:42:34.530 --> 00:42:41.030
and I can develop on top of
that basic idea or first idea.

00:42:41.030 --> 00:42:44.760
And then eventually, you come
up with moments and pieces

00:42:44.760 --> 00:42:49.600
that you're proud of,
or that you think work.

00:42:49.600 --> 00:42:52.150
But at the end of the
day, you have to do it.

00:42:52.150 --> 00:42:56.880
And if the audience
says no, you go, OK.

00:42:56.880 --> 00:42:58.840
You just go home.

00:42:58.840 --> 00:43:00.630
Then you really go home.

00:43:00.630 --> 00:43:02.810
Then you really go home.

00:43:02.810 --> 00:43:07.800
But it's those things
combine that is

00:43:07.800 --> 00:43:11.700
kind of the process to get
on stage and do something.

00:43:16.510 --> 00:43:19.960
AUDIENCE: So you tell
stories and send messages

00:43:19.960 --> 00:43:22.610
in lots of different,
I'll say, audiences,

00:43:22.610 --> 00:43:25.120
like there's 50
people here or so.

00:43:25.120 --> 00:43:27.270
You do shows where
it's 25 people.

00:43:27.270 --> 00:43:31.190
The Geffen's 120 or something.

00:43:31.190 --> 00:43:33.700
A TED Talk is a lot more,
and then social media's

00:43:33.700 --> 00:43:35.380
however many.

00:43:35.380 --> 00:43:39.360
How do those different spaces--

00:43:39.360 --> 00:43:42.610
how do you decide what
story you want to tell,

00:43:42.610 --> 00:43:44.550
or how you pick the words?

00:43:44.550 --> 00:43:47.170
How do you decide how
to convey the message

00:43:47.170 --> 00:43:48.520
in these different environments?

00:43:48.520 --> 00:43:50.560
And how does that
change, particularly

00:43:50.560 --> 00:43:54.130
when you're speaking
to a larger audience?

00:43:54.130 --> 00:43:58.570
HELDER GUIMARAES: It
does because you always

00:43:58.570 --> 00:44:04.090
have to adapt the show you do
to the room you're playing in.

00:44:04.090 --> 00:44:13.820
And of course, the more
you learn how to do it,

00:44:13.820 --> 00:44:17.290
the more easy it is to
create moments of intimacy

00:44:17.290 --> 00:44:19.230
in larger spaces.

00:44:19.230 --> 00:44:21.310
In that sense, I've--

00:44:21.310 --> 00:44:26.950
so the last show I've done in
Portugal was for 900 people.

00:44:26.950 --> 00:44:34.780
And at that point, it's not
an intimate show no longer.

00:44:34.780 --> 00:44:37.720
But it doesn't mean it can't
be an intimate experience

00:44:37.720 --> 00:44:38.920
for people.

00:44:38.920 --> 00:44:42.310
You just have to
do certain choices

00:44:42.310 --> 00:44:47.590
in terms of scenic design
and in terms of text

00:44:47.590 --> 00:44:50.020
and in terms of-- for
example, in that show

00:44:50.020 --> 00:44:53.020
there is a camera that
projects the top of the table,

00:44:53.020 --> 00:44:55.030
and there's a big screen.

00:44:55.030 --> 00:44:56.485
But you can't overuse it.

00:44:56.485 --> 00:44:58.360
Because all of the
sudden, if you overuse it,

00:44:58.360 --> 00:45:01.660
people feel that they are always
seeing things on the screen.

00:45:01.660 --> 00:45:02.950
And don't feel that.

00:45:02.950 --> 00:45:07.690
So you have to decide
and craft the show more

00:45:07.690 --> 00:45:12.130
around the technical challenges
that you're going to have.

00:45:12.130 --> 00:45:14.530
And I think the
bigger the space is,

00:45:14.530 --> 00:45:20.380
the more you have
to do it that way.

00:45:20.380 --> 00:45:22.510
In a smaller space,
where everyone

00:45:22.510 --> 00:45:25.780
can observe you and
be closer to you,

00:45:25.780 --> 00:45:30.770
then it's the story that
really drives more the creation

00:45:30.770 --> 00:45:32.180
of everything.

00:45:32.180 --> 00:45:34.390
That's why I prefer that.

00:45:34.390 --> 00:45:38.020
It's because then I can really
focus on what I want to say

00:45:38.020 --> 00:45:40.650
and how I want to
tell the story.

00:45:40.650 --> 00:45:43.120
How I go about
selecting the stories,

00:45:43.120 --> 00:45:46.870
it comes from life
experiences and moments

00:45:46.870 --> 00:45:50.080
I am living and doubts I have.

00:45:50.080 --> 00:45:56.680
It's not that rare
that I find myself

00:45:56.680 --> 00:45:59.020
doing a show to try
to answer to something

00:45:59.020 --> 00:46:01.090
I don't have an answer.

00:46:01.090 --> 00:46:02.860
Like now.

00:46:02.860 --> 00:46:06.310
This show I'm doing,
it's about how

00:46:06.310 --> 00:46:11.200
we deal with mystery in a
world that has information

00:46:11.200 --> 00:46:13.600
at the fingertips, and
that people are not

00:46:13.600 --> 00:46:18.260
willing to not know something.

00:46:18.260 --> 00:46:20.290
How many conversations
do you have

00:46:20.290 --> 00:46:23.470
per month where all of a
sudden you have a doubt,

00:46:23.470 --> 00:46:29.800
and immediately you take the
phone to answer that doubt?

00:46:29.800 --> 00:46:34.390
That's a mechanism that in
certain cases makes sense.

00:46:34.390 --> 00:46:37.690
In others, you
should not do that.

00:46:37.690 --> 00:46:43.120
You should pull a little bit
from behind of your brain

00:46:43.120 --> 00:46:46.210
and try to deal with
that in a different way.

00:46:46.210 --> 00:46:49.030
Because it can be very useful--

00:46:49.030 --> 00:46:52.410
and actually, saying this
at Google just feels weird.

00:46:52.410 --> 00:46:54.760
[LAUGHTER]

00:46:54.760 --> 00:46:58.360
But one thing is
the ability of being

00:46:58.360 --> 00:47:00.860
able to have that information.

00:47:00.860 --> 00:47:02.380
I think that's great.

00:47:02.380 --> 00:47:05.630
How we value that information
and how we use it,

00:47:05.630 --> 00:47:07.510
and how we leave
space for mystery--

00:47:07.510 --> 00:47:13.210
because mystery can be so much
important in our life as well--

00:47:13.210 --> 00:47:17.860
that balance, it's something
that I personally am always

00:47:17.860 --> 00:47:19.240
struggling to understand.

00:47:19.240 --> 00:47:22.660
And I believe other
people probably too.

00:47:22.660 --> 00:47:27.170
So the show deals a
little bit with that.

00:47:27.170 --> 00:47:29.770
And it's just a story
in the perspective

00:47:29.770 --> 00:47:34.930
from my side of the table
of maybe how we can all

00:47:34.930 --> 00:47:37.340
incorporate a little bit
more mystery in our lives.

00:47:42.600 --> 00:47:46.680
AUDIENCE: So I will
say having gotten

00:47:46.680 --> 00:47:49.082
to have the experience of
sitting with you in table

00:47:49.082 --> 00:47:51.290
and being a participant is
something that will always

00:47:51.290 --> 00:47:53.833
stick with me.

00:47:53.833 --> 00:47:55.000
HELDER GUIMARAES: Thank you.

00:47:55.000 --> 00:47:57.470
AUDIENCE: And one of
the things I realized

00:47:57.470 --> 00:47:59.930
that helped contribute
to that sense of wonder

00:47:59.930 --> 00:48:04.310
is the fact that your
style of performance

00:48:04.310 --> 00:48:08.847
was something that I had no
idea what was going to happen.

00:48:08.847 --> 00:48:10.430
But there are, of
course, other people

00:48:10.430 --> 00:48:14.342
who in their performances
set up an expectation where,

00:48:14.342 --> 00:48:16.550
for example, if it's a
prediction or something, where

00:48:16.550 --> 00:48:19.480
you sort of know what
the end goal is, right?

00:48:19.480 --> 00:48:21.720
Where you know what
they're going to do,

00:48:21.720 --> 00:48:26.300
and the question is, the
setup is that it's impossible,

00:48:26.300 --> 00:48:28.560
but they're somehow
still going to do it.

00:48:28.560 --> 00:48:31.730
What do you think draws you
towards the other style, where

00:48:31.730 --> 00:48:34.922
there isn't a clear
expectation, where someone

00:48:34.922 --> 00:48:36.380
has no idea what's
going to happen,

00:48:36.380 --> 00:48:40.700
that you haven't necessarily
set up that oh, this

00:48:40.700 --> 00:48:42.560
is the thing I'm going
towards, and instead

00:48:42.560 --> 00:48:45.560
you just surprise them?

00:48:45.560 --> 00:48:50.250
HELDER GUIMARAES: I actually
use both when I'm doing a show.

00:48:50.250 --> 00:48:54.260
I use moments like
you're saying,

00:48:54.260 --> 00:49:00.230
like setting up an expectation
and trying to deliver that.

00:49:00.230 --> 00:49:02.990
I just like the fact
that the audience

00:49:02.990 --> 00:49:09.330
is less worried about the
end and more interested

00:49:09.330 --> 00:49:10.280
in the journey.

00:49:10.280 --> 00:49:14.390
So that's why I prefer a little
bit the surprise style, as you

00:49:14.390 --> 00:49:19.370
said, has to do with that, the
idea of, where is this going?

00:49:19.370 --> 00:49:21.590
Let's live this story together.

00:49:21.590 --> 00:49:25.160
It's more on that side
that my preference takes.

00:49:25.160 --> 00:49:29.960
But in a one hour show, you
have to kind of play with that.

00:49:29.960 --> 00:49:36.590
There is actually an
article in the magic world

00:49:36.590 --> 00:49:40.070
that talks about
surprise versus suspense,

00:49:40.070 --> 00:49:46.700
and how that affects one, the
creation, other, the audience

00:49:46.700 --> 00:49:49.290
experience of the show.

00:49:49.290 --> 00:49:52.170
And I think both are valuable.

00:49:52.170 --> 00:49:55.700
And I think both play
a part on my work.

00:49:55.700 --> 00:49:59.870
I really like the
fact that I'm sharing

00:49:59.870 --> 00:50:03.900
the journey with the
audience at the same time,

00:50:03.900 --> 00:50:06.450
instead of telling
you, by the way,

00:50:06.450 --> 00:50:09.480
I already know where
this is going to end.

00:50:09.480 --> 00:50:12.830
And so now you're just
watching, but you know

00:50:12.830 --> 00:50:14.340
where this is going to end.

00:50:14.340 --> 00:50:18.560
I like that part to also be
kind of unclear and unknown,

00:50:18.560 --> 00:50:23.540
so that when it happens,
you go, wait a minute.

00:50:23.540 --> 00:50:26.005
I love that type of--

00:50:26.005 --> 00:50:28.380
it's a game almost with the
audience that you're playing.

00:50:28.380 --> 00:50:31.250
And I like that game
of the audience almost

00:50:31.250 --> 00:50:34.250
being a detective
during the process,

00:50:34.250 --> 00:50:36.830
being like, why
is he doing this?

00:50:36.830 --> 00:50:37.720
Why?

00:50:37.720 --> 00:50:39.010
Oh.

00:50:39.010 --> 00:50:41.250
I like that moment.

00:50:41.250 --> 00:50:44.450
But to be honest, it's
just because of that.

00:50:44.450 --> 00:50:48.860
I like the audience to
be in this boat with me

00:50:48.860 --> 00:50:49.700
in terms of journey.

00:50:53.548 --> 00:50:54.090
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:50:54.090 --> 00:50:55.640
HELDER GUIMARAES: Hi.

00:50:55.640 --> 00:50:59.950
AUDIENCE: So when you are
watching other performers,

00:50:59.950 --> 00:51:02.920
is it easy for you to
deconstruct their tricks

00:51:02.920 --> 00:51:05.770
and illusions, or
are you also amazed?

00:51:05.770 --> 00:51:09.370
And are there any illusions that
have stumped you to this day

00:51:09.370 --> 00:51:13.670
that you still can't
tell how they did it?

00:51:13.670 --> 00:51:21.300
HELDER GUIMARAES: It's hard to
let go the magician side of it.

00:51:21.300 --> 00:51:22.190
I admit it.

00:51:22.190 --> 00:51:24.360
So when I'm seeing
a performance,

00:51:24.360 --> 00:51:29.000
it's almost like I'm
seeing with a double brain.

00:51:29.000 --> 00:51:33.043
I'm trying to enjoy it
without thinking too much.

00:51:33.043 --> 00:51:34.460
But then there are
certain moments

00:51:34.460 --> 00:51:37.340
that definitely
click, just because I

00:51:37.340 --> 00:51:39.027
know how things are done.

00:51:39.027 --> 00:51:40.610
So all of the sudden,
it's really hard

00:51:40.610 --> 00:51:43.550
just to let it go completely.

00:51:43.550 --> 00:51:45.620
That said, that
doesn't mean that I

00:51:45.620 --> 00:51:49.350
don't appreciate a performance
when it's well done.

00:51:49.350 --> 00:51:55.160
In fact, I always say this
as a comparison situation.

00:51:55.160 --> 00:51:58.370
If you play the piano,
and you go to a concert,

00:51:58.370 --> 00:52:02.540
and someone is playing a
recital or something like that,

00:52:02.540 --> 00:52:08.210
and they are playing, and
you know how to play piano,

00:52:08.210 --> 00:52:10.520
you are listening to the
melody, but you are also

00:52:10.520 --> 00:52:13.370
listening to their
choices and how

00:52:13.370 --> 00:52:16.910
they decide to do certain
parts quicker or with more

00:52:16.910 --> 00:52:19.850
strength or all that.

00:52:19.850 --> 00:52:22.520
And so when I'm seeing a
magic performance normally,

00:52:22.520 --> 00:52:25.460
I'm also seeing those
choices and seeing

00:52:25.460 --> 00:52:28.910
where those choices will
make the audience arrive

00:52:28.910 --> 00:52:31.100
in terms of impossibility.

00:52:31.100 --> 00:52:33.540
And so I really appreciate--

00:52:33.540 --> 00:52:38.450
and sometimes it's even
more beautiful to be

00:52:38.450 --> 00:52:43.700
able to see the audience
reaction and also that.

00:52:43.700 --> 00:52:46.910
But there have been
a couple of times--

00:52:46.910 --> 00:52:50.480
I can't say that it's
the common thing--

00:52:50.480 --> 00:52:53.040
but where all of the
sudden, I'm in a moment,

00:52:53.040 --> 00:52:55.540
and I don't understand
how something happens,

00:52:55.540 --> 00:52:56.990
and I just love it.

00:52:56.990 --> 00:52:59.670
Because I don't have that
reaction that many times.

00:52:59.670 --> 00:53:01.310
So when I have it,
I really cherish.

00:53:01.310 --> 00:53:04.220
And I really-- the
only reason for me

00:53:04.220 --> 00:53:08.360
after to try to find
an answer to that

00:53:08.360 --> 00:53:11.840
is if I find any
valuable on that

00:53:11.840 --> 00:53:13.820
to be able to use on my work.

00:53:13.820 --> 00:53:17.900
But there have been, I would say
that two or three cases, where

00:53:17.900 --> 00:53:21.800
I've seen something that
I go, what I'm seeing

00:53:21.800 --> 00:53:24.900
has no relation to
my type of work.

00:53:24.900 --> 00:53:26.730
So I just prefer not to know.

00:53:26.730 --> 00:53:28.940
And I really don't.

00:53:28.940 --> 00:53:32.630
Because I don't have that
many moments like that.

00:53:32.630 --> 00:53:34.220
So I really cherish those.

00:53:34.220 --> 00:53:38.750
So I really don't want to know,
unless it can move something

00:53:38.750 --> 00:53:40.950
forward on my work.

00:53:40.950 --> 00:53:44.510
And then I probably will
search for an answer.

00:53:44.510 --> 00:53:47.550
But there are things
I really don't know.

00:53:47.550 --> 00:53:50.240
I may have a sense,
an idea, but that's

00:53:50.240 --> 00:53:52.790
different than actually knowing.

00:53:52.790 --> 00:53:55.760
That's a very
interesting difference

00:53:55.760 --> 00:53:57.920
between being a magician,
not being a magician,

00:53:57.920 --> 00:53:59.750
and seeing a magic show.

00:53:59.750 --> 00:54:05.690
If you see a magic show,
and you kind of find out 10%

00:54:05.690 --> 00:54:08.660
of what you're seeing--

00:54:08.660 --> 00:54:11.720
let's suppose what
you call the trick.

00:54:11.720 --> 00:54:14.090
I really hate the word trick.

00:54:14.090 --> 00:54:16.820
Dogs do tricks for me.

00:54:16.820 --> 00:54:21.170
But like I call them
pieces or repertoire,

00:54:21.170 --> 00:54:22.020
something like that.

00:54:22.020 --> 00:54:25.778
But imagine you're seeing a
magic piece, and you find 10%.

00:54:25.778 --> 00:54:27.320
If you are an audience
member and you

00:54:27.320 --> 00:54:30.890
know nothing about magic, you go
like oh, I know how he did it.

00:54:30.890 --> 00:54:33.690
And you just know 10%.

00:54:33.690 --> 00:54:37.520
If I am a magician, and
I'm seeing the same thing,

00:54:37.520 --> 00:54:41.990
and I know 90%, I go
like, yeah, I really

00:54:41.990 --> 00:54:43.130
don't know how he did it.

00:54:43.130 --> 00:54:49.140
Because I am aware that I'm
missing those extra 10%.

00:54:49.140 --> 00:54:52.160
So it's a very interesting
thing how we relate

00:54:52.160 --> 00:54:54.380
to knowing or not knowing.

00:54:54.380 --> 00:54:58.430
If we know a lot, we also
know what we don't know.

00:54:58.430 --> 00:55:01.340
If we know very little,
we think we know

00:55:01.340 --> 00:55:03.150
more than we actually know.

00:55:03.150 --> 00:55:03.650
It's true.

00:55:03.650 --> 00:55:05.810
It's true in any case.

00:55:05.810 --> 00:55:08.660
And with magic, you
can say that to a test.

00:55:08.660 --> 00:55:11.000
I've been in so many
interesting conversations

00:55:11.000 --> 00:55:13.220
after shows of mine
with friends that

00:55:13.220 --> 00:55:15.380
go like, I really
liked your show,

00:55:15.380 --> 00:55:18.510
but I figured this one out.

00:55:18.510 --> 00:55:20.990
And I just go like, oh really?

00:55:20.990 --> 00:55:24.300
And so I go down the road
with them and go like,

00:55:24.300 --> 00:55:26.210
so tell me how I do it.

00:55:26.210 --> 00:55:28.980
And they start
going step by step.

00:55:28.980 --> 00:55:32.990
And I know there is a hole in
the middle of the conversation

00:55:32.990 --> 00:55:38.010
where they're just going to go
like, oh, I really don't know.

00:55:38.010 --> 00:55:39.620
But I led them to that hole.

00:55:39.620 --> 00:55:41.120
Very like, oh really?

00:55:41.120 --> 00:55:44.150
[INAUDIBLE]

00:55:44.150 --> 00:55:48.980
And this-- oh, oh yeah,
I really don't know.

00:55:48.980 --> 00:55:50.750
OK, so shut up next time.

00:55:50.750 --> 00:55:53.262
Just shut up.

00:55:53.262 --> 00:55:54.337
And that's OK.

00:55:54.337 --> 00:55:55.670
To be honest with you, I'm not--

00:55:55.670 --> 00:55:59.360
if people find
out, they find out.

00:55:59.360 --> 00:56:03.360
I always say this as
a joke, but it's true.

00:56:03.360 --> 00:56:05.510
I'm very privileged
of doing what I do,

00:56:05.510 --> 00:56:08.720
because I bring joy to
people, and I make them happy,

00:56:08.720 --> 00:56:11.450
and it's entertaining.

00:56:11.450 --> 00:56:13.730
What I do falls
in the bright side

00:56:13.730 --> 00:56:17.780
of life, which for me I'm very
fortunate to be part of it.

00:56:17.780 --> 00:56:21.050
This is not like you're
curing a life death

00:56:21.050 --> 00:56:23.310
situation on a patient.

00:56:23.310 --> 00:56:27.920
And if you fail, that is tough.

00:56:27.920 --> 00:56:31.010
If I fail something
or if you find out,

00:56:31.010 --> 00:56:34.630
life goes exactly in
the same direction.

00:56:34.630 --> 00:56:38.900
So I'm not that uncomfortable
if people find out.

00:56:38.900 --> 00:56:41.030
I always try my
best to make sure

00:56:41.030 --> 00:56:43.160
that they have the
mystery for their life.

00:56:43.160 --> 00:56:45.170
That's my goal.

00:56:45.170 --> 00:56:48.860
But it's so funny to lead
people into these conversations,

00:56:48.860 --> 00:56:52.230
and having them realize that
they actually don't know.

00:56:52.230 --> 00:56:54.857
It's just really funny for me.

00:56:54.857 --> 00:56:55.690
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:56:55.690 --> 00:56:56.180
SPEAKER: Thank you.

00:56:56.180 --> 00:56:57.888
We have time for maybe
one more question.

00:57:00.387 --> 00:57:01.970
AUDIENCE: Can you
tell us a little bit

00:57:01.970 --> 00:57:03.400
about how you practice?

00:57:03.400 --> 00:57:05.930
And I'm sure at
your stage, you've

00:57:05.930 --> 00:57:07.130
mastered the double lift.

00:57:07.130 --> 00:57:09.260
But are you still doing
it 100 times a day,

00:57:09.260 --> 00:57:11.360
or what does your practice
routine look like?

00:57:11.360 --> 00:57:14.180
HELDER GUIMARAES: No, I
don't do it 100 times a day,

00:57:14.180 --> 00:57:16.640
because it's boring.

00:57:16.640 --> 00:57:22.310
But you definitely practice the
same way that you would say--

00:57:24.920 --> 00:57:29.510
there is a difference between
getting the skill to the level

00:57:29.510 --> 00:57:31.190
you want to get it,
and then keeping

00:57:31.190 --> 00:57:32.610
the skill at that level.

00:57:32.610 --> 00:57:36.290
So to keep the skill, you don't
have to technically practice

00:57:36.290 --> 00:57:37.340
that much.

00:57:37.340 --> 00:57:39.800
But you still have to
do it on a regular basis

00:57:39.800 --> 00:57:41.640
and consistent basis.

00:57:41.640 --> 00:57:45.170
But I'm always trying to
improve certain things

00:57:45.170 --> 00:57:48.980
or invent new skills
or invent new things.

00:57:48.980 --> 00:57:52.400
So I'm always focused
more on that side

00:57:52.400 --> 00:57:56.990
than necessarily keeping
the skill level where I am.

00:57:56.990 --> 00:58:00.860
Because doing that
ends up protecting

00:58:00.860 --> 00:58:03.260
what I've accomplished before.

00:58:03.260 --> 00:58:04.800
But you have to do it every day.

00:58:04.800 --> 00:58:10.310
So every day I have a few hours
that I just spend on a table,

00:58:10.310 --> 00:58:13.130
what we say shuffling
cards, which is actually not

00:58:13.130 --> 00:58:14.840
shuffling cards.

00:58:14.840 --> 00:58:19.160
But just doing a
bunch of things.

00:58:19.160 --> 00:58:21.560
And finding things.

00:58:21.560 --> 00:58:25.370
I'm always finding new
interesting details that can

00:58:25.370 --> 00:58:29.010
take things to the next step.

00:58:29.010 --> 00:58:30.500
But you do that.

00:58:30.500 --> 00:58:32.210
You do that in
front of a mirror.

00:58:32.210 --> 00:58:35.450
You do that to close friends
when you want to do something.

00:58:35.450 --> 00:58:39.380
Normally I'm at dinner with
friends, and if I want to--

00:58:39.380 --> 00:58:42.500
I normally don't like to
just do things per se,

00:58:42.500 --> 00:58:44.330
but if I want to
practice something,

00:58:44.330 --> 00:58:46.370
all of the sudden, all I have
to do is take the deck of cards

00:58:46.370 --> 00:58:48.412
and put it on the table,
because someone is going

00:58:48.412 --> 00:58:50.220
to ask me to do something.

00:58:50.220 --> 00:58:52.820
And then I go, OK, that's a
good chance to practice that,

00:58:52.820 --> 00:58:55.250
because it's a safe environment.

00:58:55.250 --> 00:59:01.070
So you find those moments
to do things like that,

00:59:01.070 --> 00:59:03.750
and to find the
audience reactions.

00:59:03.750 --> 00:59:05.390
So that then you can
incorporate those

00:59:05.390 --> 00:59:08.990
in longer pieces and
moments like a show,

00:59:08.990 --> 00:59:10.660
like I'm doing now.

00:59:10.660 --> 00:59:16.530
But yes, definitely, you have
to keep practicing every day.

00:59:16.530 --> 00:59:17.790
Unless you want to quit.

00:59:17.790 --> 00:59:21.868
And then it would be
fine not do anything.

00:59:21.868 --> 00:59:23.910
SPEAKER: OK, I think that's
all the time we have.

00:59:23.910 --> 00:59:25.465
Thank you, Helder,
so much for coming

00:59:25.465 --> 00:59:26.480
to spend some time with us.

00:59:26.480 --> 00:59:28.647
HELDER GUIMARAES: Thank you
very much for having me.

00:59:28.647 --> 00:59:31.690
[APPLAUSE]

